  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Constructing the Simulator**\n\nOkay, I\'ve got a couple of key components in place now: `NetworkGraph.tsx` and `ExcusesDilemmas.tsx`. The next step is to build the core simulator itself, `ImpactCalculator.tsx`. I\'m starting to think about the user input: it\'ll be based on their weekly consumption of various animal products.\n\n\n**Gathering Environmental Data**\n\nI\'m now diving into the environmental impact data. I\'ve begun gathering multipliers for various animal products, focusing on metrics like suffering hours, CO\342\202\202 emissions, water usage, and land usage per unit. I have data for beef, pork and chicken now. My plan is to expand this dataset to include fish, seafood, milk, eggs and any other relevant category.\n\n\n**Analyzing the Data**\n\nI\'ve just added multipliers for fish, seafood, dairy, and eggs. My focus is still on key metrics: suffering hours, CO\342\202\202 emissions, water usage, and land usage. I am now incorporating these per 100g or per unit, depending on the product, into the dataset. I\'m aiming for a comprehensive view now, and I\'ll soon move on to the next phase.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I am creating `/src/components/ImpactCalculator.tsx`. This component is an interactive, mathematically rigorous eco-moral footprint simulator designed for Spanish. The user adjusts sliders representing their weekly dietary consumption (beef, pork, chicken, fish, dairy, eggs). The calculator computes or estimates real metrics:\n- **Systemic suffering hours sponsored** (hours of animal confinement, distress, or maternal separation).\n- **Greenhouse carbon footprint (kg CO2-eq)**.\n- **Water footprint (liters of water)**.\n- **Land use footprint (m\302\262)**.\n\nIt displays these values using beautiful, custom-designed charts, compares them to a plant-based diet baseline, and suggests partial reduction targets (25%, 50%, or 100%) to show concrete metrics of what resources and hours of suffering they can spare. This triggers immediate cognitive reflection as requested by Germ\303\241n."
    thinking_duration {
